<subSubSection lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="27.[192,1440,1697,1882]" lastBlockId="28.[192,1440,1465,1521]" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,324,1826,1850]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">Remarks.</emphasis>
This distinctive species is ecologically associated with desert riparian or similar habitats including isolated desert springs, agricultural and urban canals, and irrigation channels (
<bibRefCitation author="La Rue, D. A." box="[1272,1428,1858,1882]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" pagination="23 - 37" refId="ref24046" refString="La Rue, D. A. 1998. Notes on Polyphylla Harris with a description of a new species (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Melolonthinae). Insecta Mundi 1 / 2: 23 - 37." type="journal article" year="1998">La Rue 1998</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Young, R. M." box="[240,402,1465,1489]" pageId="28" pageNumber="27" refId="ref26743" refString="Young, R. M. 1988. A monograph of the genus Polyphylla Harris in America, north of Mexico. Bulletin of the University of Nebraska State Museum 11: vi + 115 p." type="book" year="1988">Young (1988)</bibRefCitation>
cited a single record of this species from 
<collectingRegion box="[901,999,1465,1489]" country="United States of America" name="Nevada" pageId="28" pageNumber="27">Nevada</collectingRegion>
: “Mesquite, Clark County,” which is adjacent to the Virgin River.
</paragraph>
